{"id":680,"date":"2022-01-05T08:59:55","date_gmt":"2022-01-05T08:59:55","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/?p=680"},"modified":"2022-01-09T12:59:10","modified_gmt":"2022-01-09T12:59:10","slug":"use-input-output-redirection-2-etc","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/?p=680","title":{"rendered":"Use input-output redirection (>, >>, |, 2>, etc.)"},"content":{"rendered":"\n<h3>What is Redirection?<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Redirection <\/strong>is a feature in Linux such that when executing a command, you can change the standard input\/output devices. The basic workflow of any Linux command is that it takes an input and give an output.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>The standard input (stdin) device is the keyboard.<\/p><p>The standard output (stdout) device is the screen.<\/p><\/blockquote>\n\n\n\n<p>With redirection, the above standard input\/output can be changed.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3>The <strong>\u2018&gt;<\/strong>\u2018 symbol is used for output (STDOUT) redirection.<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We can try this by using command bellow:<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">ls -a &gt; output_of_ls_command<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"640\" height=\"322\" src=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-49.png?resize=640%2C322&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-681\" srcset=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-49.png?w=836&amp;ssl=1 836w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-49.png?resize=300%2C151&amp;ssl=1 300w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-49.png?resize=768%2C386&amp;ssl=1 768w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-49.png?resize=24%2C12&amp;ssl=1 24w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-49.png?resize=36%2C18&amp;ssl=1 36w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-49.png?resize=48%2C24&amp;ssl=1 48w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p>You should be aware of the correct file name while redirecting command output to a file. If there is an existing file with the same name, the redirected command will delete the contents of that file and then <strong>it may be overwritten<\/strong>.\u201d<\/p>\n\n\n\n<blockquote class=\"wp-block-quote\"><p>If you do not want a file to be overwritten but want to add more content to an existing file, then you should use <strong>\u2018&gt;&gt;<\/strong>\u2018 operator.<\/p><\/blockquote>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3>The <strong>\u2018&lt;<\/strong>\u2018 symbol is used for input(STDIN) redirection<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>We could for example have some script or some command that need input to work and feed could feed it information with the STDIN redirection<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre id=\"block-214a6cf7-e1c3-445a-8bcb-343a55eba0bf\" class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">.\/test.sh &lt; input_info.txt<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h3>Error Redirection (STDERR)<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>Whenever you execute a program\/command at the terminal, 3 files are always open {<strong>standard input, standard output, standard error}<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"399\" height=\"141\" src=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/process.png?resize=399%2C141&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-682\" srcset=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/process.png?w=399&amp;ssl=1 399w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/process.png?resize=300%2C106&amp;ssl=1 300w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/process.png?resize=24%2C8&amp;ssl=1 24w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/process.png?resize=36%2C13&amp;ssl=1 36w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/process.png?resize=48%2C17&amp;ssl=1 48w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 399px) 100vw, 399px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>By default, error output is displayed on the screen. Error redirection is routing the errors to a file other than the screen.<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<h4>What even is Error Redirection?<\/h4>\n\n\n\n<p>Error re-direction is one of the very popular features of Unix\/Linux.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<ul><li>For instance, while searching for files, one typically gets permission denied errors. These errors usually do not help the person searching for a particular file.<\/li><li>While executing shell scripts, you often do NOT want error messages cluttering up the normal program output.<\/li><\/ul>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>But we can for example re-direct the error messages to a file:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">$ test 2&gt;errorsfile<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Let\u2019s see a more real life scenario:<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>Server Administrators frequently, list directories and store both error and standard output into a file, which can be processed later<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">ls -a Desktop bla&gt; ls_output_file 2&gt;&amp;1<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>One very useful example is when the text of the screen is basically unreadable because of all the error messages (permission denied for example) and <strong>we just simply redirect output from the screen to the<\/strong> <strong>\/dev\/null in which <\/strong>everything is discarded<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image is-style-default\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-large\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"640\" height=\"288\" src=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-77.png?resize=640%2C288&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-753\" srcset=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-77.png?resize=1024%2C461&amp;ssl=1 1024w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-77.png?resize=300%2C135&amp;ssl=1 300w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-77.png?resize=768%2C346&amp;ssl=1 768w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-77.png?resize=24%2C11&amp;ssl=1 24w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-77.png?resize=36%2C16&amp;ssl=1 36w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-77.png?resize=48%2C22&amp;ssl=1 48w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-77.png?w=1265&amp;ssl=1 1265w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>But simply redirecting error output as I said will do the trick<\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">grep -R thetechcorner \/etc 2>\/dev\/null<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"wp-block-image is-style-default\"><figure class=\"aligncenter size-full\"><img decoding=\"async\" loading=\"lazy\" width=\"640\" height=\"86\" src=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-78.png?resize=640%2C86&#038;ssl=1\" alt=\"\" class=\"wp-image-755\" srcset=\"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-78.png?w=760&amp;ssl=1 760w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-78.png?resize=300%2C40&amp;ssl=1 300w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-78.png?resize=24%2C3&amp;ssl=1 24w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-78.png?resize=36%2C5&amp;ssl=1 36w, https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/image-78.png?resize=48%2C6&amp;ssl=1 48w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" data-recalc-dims=\"1\" \/><\/figure><\/div>\n\n\n\n<h3>Using a pipe or |<\/h3>\n\n\n\n<p>A <strong>pipe <\/strong>is a form of redirection (transfer of standard output to some other destination) that is used in Linux and other Unix-like operating systems to send the output of one command\/program\/process to another command\/program\/process for further processing. The Unix\/Linux systems allow stdout of a command to be connected to stdin of another command. You can make it do so by using the pipe character \u2018|\u2019.<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>It can also be visualized as a temporary connection between two or more commands. <\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<div class=\"is-layout-flow wp-block-group\"><div class=\"wp-block-group__inner-container\">\n<pre class=\"wp-block-preformatted\">command_1 | command_2 | command_3 | .... | command_N&nbsp;<\/pre>\n<\/div><\/div>\n\n\n\n<p><strong>Example :<\/strong><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>We can list all the files in the directory and pipe into a head command which will list only the first 10 options<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>$ ls -l | head<\/p>\n\n\n\n<p><\/p>\n\n\n\n<p>There is much more we do with redirections and pipes, but again this will be mentioned in a later chapter of RHCSA.<\/p>\n","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>What is Redirection? Redirection is a feature in Linux such that when executing a command, [&hellip;]<\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":1,"featured_media":751,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"open","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"nf_dc_page":"","om_disable_all_campaigns":false,"_mi_skip_tracking":false},"categories":[219],"tags":[233,231,232,234,235,220,238,237,236,230],"jetpack_featured_media_url":"https:\/\/i0.wp.com\/thetechcorner.org\/wp-content\/uploads\/2022\/01\/rhsa-understand-and-use-essential-tools-2.png?fit=1280%2C720&ssl=1","_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts\/680"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/users\/1"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=%2Fwp%2Fv2%2Fcomments&post=680"}],"version-history":[{"count":3,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts\/680\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":756,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/posts\/680\/revisions\/756"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=\/wp\/v2\/media\/751"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=%2Fwp%2Fv2%2Fmedia&parent=680"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=%2Fwp%2Fv2%2Fcategories&post=680"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/thetechcorner.org\/index.php?rest_route=%2Fwp%2Fv2%2Ftags&post=680"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}